// The problem was due to type "int main()", in order to solve the aforementioned problem, we need to make the
// function name unique and rename it such that we can be able to run it. One solution is to append the type to the
// main function name, which I do not like because in languages like C, "main" is just reserved name and cannot be used.
// Another solution might be to put the code inside if statement around main function, but the solution might have some
// unwanted side effects where the undesired function names might be executed like if main function is renamed, the code
// that might belong to the main function might be removed as well; this solution might be very hard to follow because
// when we rename the main function, we do not have a way of knowing which functions are associated with main function
// but the code is inside of if statement, therefore if the compiler encounters code inside of if statement, it will
// remove any code that is not associated with if statement. Another approach is to use macros to rename the main function
// such that the function is unique:
// #include <iostream>
// using namespace std;
// #define MAIN_A main();
// #include 198.fuzz
// The 198.fuzz contains the required code:
#define MAIN_A do { std::cout << 10 << std::endl; std::cout << 20 << std::endl; std::cout << 30 << std::endl;} while(false);
int main_a ()
{
  // CODE INSIDE MAIN_A FUNCTION //
}
